23
00:00:59,140 --> 00:01:03,010
One of the fun parts is you see all the executives sitting around the table,

24
00:01:03,010 --> 00:01:04,200
and they're brainstorming.

25
00:01:04,200 --> 00:01:08,230
And Don Draper becomes creative-- one of the executives in the show--

26
00:01:08,230 --> 00:01:10,160
and they come up with a great idea.

27
00:01:10,160 --> 00:01:14,120
And then the big machine starts to work, and the campaign unfolds.

28
00:01:14,120 --> 00:01:15,860
And the process takes months.

29
00:01:15,860 --> 00:01:16,420
Right?

30
00:01:16,420 --> 00:01:19,020
And that's, to be honest, historically, the way

31
00:01:19,020 --> 00:01:22,130
that advertising communication happens-- is

32
00:01:22,130 --> 00:01:25,330
it's a nice long period of time where something

33
00:01:25,330 --> 00:01:28,310
really thoughtful and creative is brought to the market

34
00:01:28,310 --> 00:01:32,130
to help sell a product or do something of the sort.

35
00:01:32,130 --> 00:01:32,670
Right?

36
00:01:32,670 --> 00:01:37,370
But real time marketing is the idea that, instead of having this long time

37
00:01:37,370 --> 00:01:43,710
span-- right-- instead, you can take advantage of events or incidents

38
00:01:43,710 --> 00:01:47,360
or things that happen in the world around us

39
00:01:47,360 --> 00:01:51,850
and you can use those events in your marketing campaign, your communication

40
00:01:51,850 --> 00:01:53,680
campaign immediately.

41
00:01:53,680 --> 00:01:57,890
So in other words, instead of doing this long drawn out process of building

42
00:01:57,890 --> 00:02:00,240
your communication campaign, you do it-

43
